Sorry to break it to you keyuchu, but you've just shown everyone here that you're actually the stupid fucktard dumbass.

720p means 1280 pixel-wide, progressive scan video.  It's a measure of the resolution of a video file, no matter what the original source is.

In the common aspect ratio of 16:9, that means the source will be 720 pixels high, but quite often it is less than that because of wider aspect ratios of cinema releases, for example 2.11:1.

So now that you've learned what "720p" really means...

If I am looking for a CAM release of a movie that isn't going to be out on BDRIP or DVDRIP for quite some time, I would certainly rather have one done with a 720p-capable camera than some old-school 480p Sony Handycam shit.

So, the first place I generally look is for Froggie's 720p uploads, which (not always, but more often than not) are better quality than lower resolution cams of the same movie. Even when they come from the same source as other releases, the upscaling gives you a noticeable improvement, especially on a large (40"+) TV.

The fact that these CAMs are of higher resolution than most others quite rightly entitles them to be placed in the HighRes section, where they can be more easily found by those who want them.

"High Resolution" does not automatically mean high quality Blu-Ray.  If that's what you're looking for, then search for "BRRIP" or "BDRIP" instead of "CAM" or "TS".
